<div id="review_1503688702" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1503688702" />
    <a title="Chris_P" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/44309339-chris-p"><img alt="Chris_P" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1558554241p2/44309339.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1503688702?book_show_action=true">Jan 10, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chris_P" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chris_P" href="/user/show/44309339-chris-p">Chris_P</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/44309339-chris-p?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1503688702" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13194871237721054895">The only thing that&apos;s thought-provoking about this book is the fact that it&apos;s sold millions of copies and is considered good by the vast majority.<br/><br/>It bored me to death! Most (if not all) of the questions are simply useless. I mean why would I even give a fuck &quot;what would happen if you were to gather a mole of moles in one place&quot;, or &quot;how many unique English tweets are possible and how long it would take for the population of the world to read them out loud&quot; (what the fuck???), or &quot;if you call a r</span>
  <span id="freeText13194871237721054895" style="display:none">The only thing that's thought-provoking about this book is the fact that it's sold millions of copies and is considered good by the vast majority.<br /><br />It bored me to death! Most (if not all) of the questions are simply useless. I mean why would I even give a fuck "what would happen if you were to gather a mole of moles in one place", or "how many unique English tweets are possible and how long it would take for the population of the world to read them out loud" (what the fuck???), or "if you call a random phone number and say god bless you, what are the chances that the person who answers just sneezed", or "what would happen if you tried to fly a normal Earth airplane in space"? This definitely isn't what I call educating. It's not even fun as a matter of fact. What's more, the answers given are absurdly complicated. Munroe in order to fill the pages, adds more useless factors making it even more boring and thus forcing you to think "why on earth am I reading this?". Honestly I haven't seen so much useless information gathered together ever before. The extra star goes for the author's occasionally witty sense of humor.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13194871237721054895" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


